<div class='desire-content'>
  <div class='desires-list'>
    <figure>
      <div class="post-autor">
        <a href="#">
          <div class="usual-avatar" style="background:url(https://pp.vk.me/c5382/v5382599/a70/lVMwRxI_h3w.jpg) no-repeat; background-size:cover;"></div>
          <div class="post-autor-info">
            <h4 class="modal-title" id="myModalLabel">Анастасия Носкова</h4>
            <div class='city-time'>
              <span>Уфа</span>
              <span>, </span>
              <span>24 апр.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
      <div class='post-content-title-text-img'>
        <a href='#'>
          <div class='wrap-title-text'>
            <h3>
              How does your bot say ‘ketchup’?
            </h3>
            <div>
              I didn’t know, so I explored by attempting to make a simple bot to help my family to order in delivery. This proved surprisingly difficult for me. Not because of the technology: as a designer-who-can-code-some, the technical ease of building a bot was exciting. No, the issue I faced wasn’t an argument in code but rather my childhood dinner table: whether to accept ‘catsup’ as a substitute for saying ‘ketchup’.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class='wrap-img'>
            <img src = 'https://pp.vk.me/c626122/v626122806/22ff/pMDsES72Ydw.jpg' />
          </div>
          <div class='clearboth'>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
      <div class='post-footer'>
        <span>16 ответов</span>
      </div>
    </figure>
  </div>
</div>
<div class='feed-content'>
  <div id="grid-gallery" class="grid-gallery">
    <div class='tips-and-comments title-under-hat'>
      <div>Публикации от тех, кого Вы читаете</div>
      <%= link_to fresh_path do%>Посмотреть все свежие публикации<% end %>
    </div>
    <% if current_user.follow_count.zero? %>
      <div class='align-c'>
        <h1>Вы пока еще никого не читаете</h1>
      </div>
    <% else %>
      <%= react_component 'Gallery', posts_url: posts_path(@user) %>
    <% end %>
  </div>
</div>